04723nam a22005535i 9780226811451DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021019307  a97802268114517 a10.7208/chicago/97802268114512doi  a(DE-B1597)590694  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN56.A67bP75 2022 4aPN56 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.933581 aPrica, Aleksandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDecay and Afterlife :bForm, Time, and the Textuality of Ruins, 1100 to 1900 /cAleksandra Prica. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tI Foundations -- t1 Among Ruins: Martin Heidegger and Sigmund Freud -- t2 Afterlife: Hans Blumenberg and Walter Benjamin -- tII The Propitious Moment -- t3 Petrarch and the View of Rome -- t4 Poliphilo and the Dream of Ruins -- tIII Living On -- t5 Ferdinand Gregorovius, Hildebert of Lavardin, and the Rupture of Continuity -- t6 Lucius Annaeus Seneca, Martin Opitz, and the Overcoming of Vanity -- tIV The Battleground of Time -- t7 Johann Jacob Breitinger, Andreas Gryphius, and the Reconsideration of Allegory -- t8 Thomas Burnet, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel, and the Realignment of Discourses -- tV Futures and Ruins -- t9 Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Georg Simmel, and the Provisionality of Forms -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCovering 800 years of intellectual and literary history, Prica considers the textual forms of ruins. Western ruins have long been understood as objects riddled with temporal contradictions, whether they appear in baroque poetry and drama, Romanticism’s nostalgic view of history, eighteenth-century paintings of classical subjects, or even recent photographic histories of the ruins of postindustrial Detroit. Decay and Afterlife pivots away from our immediate, visual fascination with ruins, focusing instead on the textuality of ruins in works about disintegration and survival. Combining an impressive array of literary, philosophical, and historiographical works both canonical and neglected, and encompassing Latin, Italian, French, German, and English sources, Aleksandra Prica addresses ruins as textual forms, examining them in their extraordinary geographical and temporal breadth, highlighting their variability and reflexivity, and uncovering new lines of aesthetic and intellectual affinity. Through close readings, she traverses eight hundred years of intellectual and literary history, from Seneca and Petrarch to Hegel, Goethe, and Georg Simmel. She tracks European discourses on ruins as they metamorphose over time, identifying surprising resemblances and resonances, ignored contrasts and tensions, as well as the shared apprehensions and ideas that come to light in the excavation of these discourses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAntiquities in literature. 0aEuropean literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRuins in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  atextuality of ruins, textual forms, discourses on ruins, discontinuous, temporal complexity, dialogical pairing, decay, afterlife, Middle Ages, early modern period.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226811451423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226811451/orig